english:
  title: Record of the Pavilion of Reflections on Antiquity in Yeongju
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the intercalary month of the year Gapja during the Zhizheng era, I journeyed from Hanju through Yeongju toward the capital. The prefect of that district, Lord Seong, asked me to name a pavilion in his prefecture, saying: "Long ago, when our Great Ancestor sought to conquer Baekje, a diviner spoke these words: 'If you build a fortification and review your armies upon the land of the Three Dragons Contending for the Pearl—that place beneath the character-shaped city—then sovereignty over the Three Hans awaits you, ready to be grasped.' Thus he surveyed the land's spiritual currents and established this city, stationing one hundred thousand soldiers. Through this, he was able to vanquish the house of Hyeon. The place where these armies encamped came to be called the Drum Court. So it is recorded in the prefecture's annals. In former times, a pavilion stood at the Drum Court, overlooking the official road, and the very configuration spoken of—where the dragons contend for the pearl—lies beneath the eaves themselves, while the character-shaped mountain forms the very shape the ancients beheld. I grieved to see this pavilion fallen into decay and namelessness, losing its significance. Now I have removed the old structure and rebuilt it anew, expanded and restored. I humbly request you give it a name, so that people might know this pavilion was not raised carelessly, but with purpose."

    I know Yeongju well—my own province lies but three hundred li distant, and I have passed through many times. Yet I also know why Yeongju remained Yeongju: the common folk lack steady livelihood, officials lack permanence, and few spare thought for pavilions and terraces. In the spring of Byungsu, I came on official business. Then, the administrator was Lord Yi Gwi-il, who transformed wasteland into fields and cleared paths through thorny brambles. I recognized him as a worthy official. Last autumn, returning from honoring my parents, I found Lord Seong had governed but half a year—yet in comparison to Lord Yi's administration, he had surpassed it considerably. Within mere months of taking office, he understood the people's circumstances completely. He promoted what benefited them and diligently removed what harmed. He encouraged agriculture and learning, equalized taxation, and aided the starving. When the people grew pleased and obedient, he issued a proclamation: "Do you know whence you come? This is the land where royal destiny was established; here stands the sacred shrine of our Great Ancestor. Yet now its halls crumble—the roof leaks, the walls crack. The spirit finds no refuge. How dare we claim to receive the blessings we do not deserve? To be human and forget what we owe our origins is impiety itself. The guest halls and public offices exist to honor visitors and uphold the dignity of government. Yet all lie abandoned. This shows contempt. Impiety and negligence alike bring judgment; this burden falls not only on those who guard the land, but even you people cannot escape such reckoning."

    All replied: "We shall obey." Thus the entire prefecture—both the powerful and the humble—contributed equally. They prepared timber, fired tiles, and first renovated the sacred shrine, its ceremonial halls, and purification chambers, crafting them noble and magnificent. The spirit was given proper residence; the ceremonies grew solemn. Then the public halls were tended and rebuilt, encouraged and overseen, with the hope that before year's end, in the idle season after harvest, all would be completed without exception.

    Word came that the court was appointing new administrators, so he said: "I shall depart. You may cease work. Record the tally of timber and tiles, preserve it, and warn those in charge not to lose a single piece. Wait for your new magistrate to complete my work."

    Soon after, he declared: "This pavilion commands the finest prospect of the prefecture and stands at the crossroads where four paths converge. It cannot remain unbuilt." He set a date and saw it finished.

    Ah, Lord Seong, seeing that this land bears the lingering grace of the royal founder, gazes upon the ancestral visage with reverence, contemplating the solemn bearing of those who first established the realm. In worship and awe, he strolls through the Drum Court, where the footsteps of ancient armies echo in memory. With longing, with admiration, how could he not exhaust every power of heart and hand to repay what he owes and restore what was lost? This is why his deeds take such form. Thus I name his pavilion: The Pavilion of Reflections on Antiquity. Though the pavilion itself is small and unworthy of record, through it one glimpses all the rest. So I have set down this account.

    Lord Seong's name is Won-gyu. He hails from Changnyeong and is the grandson of Dong-am, a celebrated name among the great families of the East. Recorded this ninth day of the month.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Three Dragons Contending for the Pearl' (三龍爭珠) is a geomantic formation believed to confer power to unite the three Korean kingdoms.
    - The 'character-shaped city' refers to the topography resembling the Chinese character 王 (wang, king).
    - The Great Ancestor (太祖) refers to Taejo of Goguryeo, legendary founder of that dynasty.
    - Yeongju was traditionally believed to be where Goguryeo's founder established his sacred shrine.
    - The Gapja year in Zhizheng era corresponds to 1364; 'Byungsu' corresponds to 1366.
